Looking at the code, I can identify a resource leak issue in the `parse` method. When `url.openStream()` is called, it opens an `InputStream` that is wrapped in an `InputStreamReader`. However, if an exception occurs during the `CSVParser` constructor (e.g., during `initializeHeader()`), the opened stream will never be closed, causing a resource leak.

The fix is to ensure the `InputStreamReader` is properly closed if the constructor fails. This can be done by opening the stream in a try-catch block and closing it on error, or by passing the responsibility to the `CSVParser` constructor to handle cleanup.

The minimal fix is to wrap the stream opening and parser construction in a try-catch that ensures cleanup on failure:

```json
{
  "fixed_code": [
    "public static CSVParser parse(final URL url, final Charset charset, final CSVFormat format) throws IOException {
        Assertions.notNull(url, "url");
        Assertions.notNull(charset, "charset");
        Assertions.notNull(format, "format");

        final InputStreamReader reader = new InputStreamReader(url.openStream(), charset);
        try {
            return new CSVParser(reader, format, 0L, 1L);
        } catch (final IOException | RuntimeException e) {
            try {
                reader.close();
            } catch (final IOException ex) {
                e.addSuppressed(ex);
            }
            throw e;
        }
    }",
    "public CSVParser(final Reader reader, final CSVFormat format, final long characterOffset, final long recordNumber)
            throws IOException {
        Assertions.notNull(reader, "reader");
        Assertions.notNull(format, "format");

        this.format = format;
        this.lexer = new Lexer(format, new ExtendedBufferedReader(reader));
        this.headerMap = this.initializeHeader();
        this.characterOffset = characterOffset;
        this.recordNumber = recordNumber - 1;
    }",
    "public Iterator<CSVRecord> iterator() {
        return new Iterator<CSVRecord>() {
        private CSVRecord current;

        private CSVRecord getNextRecord() {
            try {
                return CSVParser.this.nextRecord();
            } catch (final IOException e) {
                throw new IllegalStateException(
                        e.getClass().getSimpleName() + " reading next record: " + e.toString(), e);
            }
        }

        @Override
        public boolean hasNext() {
            if (CSVParser.this.isClosed()) {
                return false;
            }
            if (this.current == null) {
                this.current = this.getNextRecord();
            }

            return this.current != null;
        }

        @Override
        public CSVRecord next() {
            if (CSVParser.this.isClosed()) {
                throw new NoSuchElementException("CSVParser has been closed");
            }
            CSVRecord next = this.current;
            this.current = null;

            if (next == null) {
                next = this.getNextRecord();
                if (next == null) {
                    throw new NoSuchElementException("No more CSV records available");
                }
            }

            return next;
        }

        @Override
        public void remove() {
            throw new UnsupportedOperationException();
        }
    };
    }"
  ]
}
